WEBVTT

00:00:03.819 --> 00:00:09.512
I think because of my working life, I'm really drawn to pieces that were used to

00:00:09.512 --> 00:00:15.467
create iconic images at the time, because that shows me that the fashion editors,

00:00:15.467 --> 00:00:20.809
the Grace Coddingtons and the Tony Goodmans of the 30s and 40s and 50s were

00:00:20.809 --> 00:00:24.399
thinking, this is the key piece that represents.

00:00:25.069 --> 00:00:26.790
the designer's work this season.

00:00:26.950 --> 00:00:30.670
I am Hamish Bowles, international editor at large for Vogue magazine.

00:00:31.049 --> 00:00:34.830
I travel the world seeking out the most singular pieces to add to my couture

00:00:34.830 --> 00:00:38.130
collection, a collection which I've spent nearly a lifetime assembling.

00:00:38.630 --> 00:00:42.169
If it's out there, I'll find it on Vintage Bowles.

00:00:43.830 --> 00:00:48.069
Today I am going to a dealer on the left bank in Paris.

00:00:48.889 --> 00:00:51.970
She's someone I've really known for decades now.

00:00:52.229 --> 00:00:53.110
Good to see you.

00:01:16.389 --> 00:01:20.949
Every now and then she has a great couture or fashion item that would interest me,

00:01:20.989 --> 00:01:24.739
so it's always worth. having a look, and she's a great colorful character.

00:01:25.379 --> 00:01:27.919
She certainly understands when she has something good.

00:01:31.300 --> 00:01:36.620
I think I was a

00:01:36.620 --> 00:01:40.680
fashion student at St. Martin's quite a long time ago, I can tell you.

00:01:41.199 --> 00:01:45.639
Everything is mixed in. I mean, you have to have a taste for going through racks and

00:01:45.639 --> 00:01:49.879
racks and racks of clothes, which luckily I have not lost that taste.

00:01:50.440 --> 00:01:53.239
I actually really enjoy things that are not curated,

00:01:53.279 --> 00:01:57.059
that are thrown together like that, because it sort of makes the hunt a little bit

00:01:57.059 --> 00:01:57.819
more exciting.

00:01:58.279 --> 00:02:03.819
There was a Dior two-piece linen ensemble from 1952.

00:02:03.940 --> 00:02:08.919
Quite simple and low-key, but had this really amazing technique of kind of knot

00:02:08.919 --> 00:02:11.979
embroidery. This is all done by hand.

00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:16.419
Actually, from a distance, it would just look like a print or the design, but...

00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:21.500
The wearer and anyone getting super close to her would understand that it was

00:02:21.500 --> 00:02:24.860
actually an incredible feat of embroidery,

00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:30.179
and that's just the kind of outrageous couture detail that a house like Christian

00:02:30.179 --> 00:02:34.160
Dior specialized in, something that was just so outrageously luxurious,

00:02:34.220 --> 00:02:39.000
but maybe only the wearer herself and her lady's maid would really understand that.

00:02:39.789 --> 00:02:42.789
And then she had a Pierre Cardin piece from about 1960,

00:02:43.009 --> 00:02:47.470
which is interesting because it's when Cardin was still kind of linked to an idea

00:02:47.470 --> 00:02:53.470
of... 50s couture, he began his working life as a tailor at Christian Dior.

00:02:53.589 --> 00:02:59.350
When he established his own house, his aesthetic was very much in that kind of mid

00:02:59.350 --> 00:03:00.789
-century haute couture world.

00:03:01.009 --> 00:03:06.350
Later into the 60s, he became one of the kind of futurist fashion

00:03:06.350 --> 00:03:11.929
gurus. So sort of just as a historic document, it's interesting to see a piece from

00:03:12.539 --> 00:03:16.479
from that transition period where you still have a sense of 50s couture and you

00:03:16.479 --> 00:03:21.520
don't really have a sense of the maverick, forward-thinking guy to come.

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:21.520
